TITLE: Defining a Module-level 'makeExtension' Factory - Python
DESCRIPTION: This example demonstrates defining the required 'makeExtension' function at the module level alongside a custom extension class, enabling Markdown to instantiate the extension dynamically when only the module path is provided. The 'MyExtension' class must inherit from 'markdown.extensions.Extension'. The 'makeExtension' function accepts '**kwargs', forwarding them to the class constructor, and returns an instance. This pattern simplifies extension loading for users by eliminating the need to specify class names, providing a single entry point per module.
SOURCE: https://github.com/virtuozzo/cloudscripting-docs/blob/master/3rdparty/markdown/docs/extensions/api.md#2025-04-23_snippet_20

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
class MyExtension(markdown.extensions.Extension)
    # Define extension here...

def makeExtension(**kwargs):
    return MyExtension(**kwargs)

```

