TITLE: OrderedDict Basic Insertion and Retrieval - Pycon
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to create an OrderedDict in Python, insert key-value pairs with standard item assignment, and inspect their order via the items() method. The OrderedDict maintains insertion order, but using special methods like add() can provide finer control over location. This example requires the markdown.odict.OrderedDict class. The expected output shows the preserved item order. Inputs are ordered key-value inserts using both direct assignment and add(), outputs are OrderedDict items/values in order.
SOURCE: https://github.com/virtuozzo/cloudscripting-docs/blob/master/3rdparty/markdown/docs/extensions/api.md#2025-04-23_snippet_10

LANGUAGE: pycon
CODE:
```
>>> from markdown.odict import OrderedDict
>>> od = OrderedDict()
>>> od['one'] =  1           # The same as: od.add('one', 1, '_begin')
>>> od['three'] = 3          # The same as: od.add('three', 3, '>one')
>>> od['four'] = 4           # The same as: od.add('four', 4, '_end')
>>> od.items()
[("one", 1), ("three", 3), ("four", 4)]
```

